          • [ - ] SteveHyland - member since 03-Nov-12

            This is far from a guaranteed Benfica progression. The cacophony and general intimidating atmosphere of the Westfalenstadion has made better teams than this Benfica one crumble. I only saw the highlights of this game, but it seemed like Aubameyang had a royal stinker. It's highly unlikely he'll play that bad in the return leg (or that he'll be allowed to take any penalties :-p ) and in any case, Dortmund seemed to make the running in this game despite being away from home. That will be magnified at home (they will spend 60%+ of the match with the ball, not 55% as they did tonight) so a 1-0 first leg deficit is hardly irretrievable. Ultimately it depends on who scores first. If it is Benfica, then it starts to look dodgy for Dortmund because playing open enough to score 3 will (in theory) also present opportunities on the counter for the Reds. If Dortmund score first however (and are up for it) then I can see them getting a few. I would say Dortmund slight favourites as it stands.
